description.value: Wooden stool with lattice bracing: lattice bracing gracefully fills the voids between the four legs of the stool. The sides alternate in the use of one and two vertical struts, one for the shorter sides and two for the longer. A feature common in latticework stools is the slightly higher stretchers on the shorter sides, which not only preserve the strength of the wood by separating pairs of mortise-and-tenon joints but also gently offset any monotony in the design. The double-cove seat is formed of curved strips of wood with four slats in the centre. The wood was either steamed and bent or cut to shape. The surface has been gessoed and painted white.

description.value: Ebony stool: the finest surviving example of its type, this stool combines precious materials and successful design with superlative craftsmanship. The leather seat dips in a double cove to give contoured support to the body from any of its four sides. Ivory inlay imitating garlands of lotus petals adorns the upper portions of the legs, contrasting brightly with the rich, dark tone of the ebony. Below the lotus garlands are miniature squares of ivory imitating through joints. The supporting lattice bracing, composed of two inner vertical struts on each side, flanked by two angled struts, is also of ivory. Stretchers of ebony terminating in ivory ferrules, which fan out in imitation of a papyrus umbel, hold the legs firmly in place. The legs taper toward the bottom and then flare out again to form a delicate, aesthetically balanced support. Incised rings ornament the tapered half.

description.value: Terracotta jar-stopper. Probably from an amphora. Top face has been stamped or pressed onto a one-piece mould, then given a matt red slip. Stamped impression of a bull’s head (boukranion) within a circle, surrounded by pointed-oval leaves or buds alternating with studs, all in relief. The back is roughly rounded. Brown Nile silt with red core typical of the Western Nile Delta. Frequent fine gold and silver mica <0.2mm, frequent off white (limestone) <2mm inclusions as well as fine organic vesicles, clay pellets (dung?) and very fine quartz. Traces of plaster adhere around the outside and bottom of the stopper, where it would have been attached to the amphora neck. Bottom was chipped, presumably when removed from amphora.

In front of the snake is either the letter I, or perhaps the tip of its tail; also a rough raised area, perhaps fortuitous, but probably obliterated letters. At the rear are a series of grooves, arranged in a grid pattern, probably to key it to a mud or plaster sub-stopper.  Produced by pressing in a one-piece mould. Micaceous red-brown Nile silt.

description.value: Big fragment of a clay sealing with a convex outer surface, probably following a larger vessel or similar object, used as jar stopper, with an approximate diameter of 30 to 35 cm. The object has two rear sides so that it has a triangular section. One rear shows two parallel lines slightly raised above the surface that might be impressions caused by the ribbing of a vessel. Also a larger inclusion of a white lime fragment is visible on this side. The second underside shows a slightly uneven surface and an area of rectangular voids that might originate from organic material as larger charcoal particles are still visible in the clay here. The outer surface shows seven impressions of a small circular seal with a motif that was cut only very shallow and is therefore not visible anymore.
